article.description: Lauren Jackson scored 21 of her 30 points in the second half when the Seattle Storm broke open a close game and went on to an 84-71 victory over the winless Houston Comets on Friday night.
article.headline: Jackson's second half outburst leads Storm past Comets
article.linkText: Jackson scores 30 as Storm romp Comets, 84-71
article.story:
SEATTLE -- Lauren Jackson found that when she's firing up
3-pointers, sometimes it's best just to catch the ball and shoot
without thinking.

	   Jackson scored 21 of her 30 points in the second half Friday
night when the Seattle Storm broke open a close game and went on to
an 84-71 victory over the winless Houston Comets.

	   Jackson hit three 3-pointers in the fourth quarter and matched
her career high with five in the game. She had five 3s against
Houston in 2001.

	   "In the last quarter, I was just throwing them up," she said.
"I don't even know what I was thinking. It was just one of those
things where I grab it, shoot it and it went in."

	   Jackson made a 3-pointer and a baseline jumper at the start of
the fourth quarter to give the Storm (5-4) a 14-point lead. She
made 5-of-7 3-point attempts in the game.

	   Hamchetou Maiga-Ba led the Comets (0-9) with 18 points, while
Tina Thompson and Michelle Snow both had 12. The Comets are off to
the second-worst start in WNBA history. Detroit started 0-13 in
2002.

	   Jackson, who also had seven rebounds, scored four points early
in the second half to give the Storm a nine-point lead before the
Comets rallied within 52-50 midway through the third quarter. But
Jackson scored five points and Betty Lennox had four as the Storm
took a 63-54 lead at the end of the quarter.

	   Lennox was 9-for-9 from the free throw line and finished with 18
points. She made her first three shots from the field as she broke
out of a recent shooting slump.

	   "It was kind of like a burden lifted off my shoulders," Lennox
said. "Once I get my confidence I can pretty much do anything. My
confidence is not where it needs to be. It's not a good feeling
when you're in a shooting slump. But tonight was a step ahead and I
needed that."

	   The Storm were 27-of-33 from the line while the Comets were
11-of-12.

	   "We were settling for jumpers and not attacking the basket,"
Comets coach Karleen Thompson said. "They had 33 free throw
attempts to our 12. They were definitely the aggressor. They came
out to win."

	   Seattle was coming off a 90-62 loss at Indiana on Wednesday.
Indiana used a zone defense that frustrated the Storm as they
missed numerous 3-pointers and failed to drive to the basket.

	   The Comets tried using a zone as well, but Seattle responded
with an outside and inside game.

	   "We kind of penetrated and kicked and that kept us all
moving," Lennox said. "That's what we didn't do at the beginning,
but we finished it at the end."

	   It turned into a physical game as the Comets had 26 fouls to 15
for the Storm. Several of the fouls were hard fouls.

	   "It was a bit of a football match for a minute," Jackson said.
"But it's fun playing like that when it's rough and everyone is
getting into it."

	   Jackson figured the game might get physical as the Comets tried
to get their first victory of the season.

	   "They haven't won any games so when they're close to getting a
game they're going to put the pedal to the metal," Jackson said.
"They're due for a win and they are going to fight to the very
end."
